<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900803-0127</DOCNO><DOCID>900803-0127.</DOCID><HL>   Toyota, Fujitsu Agree   To Form a Company   To Develop Software   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>08/03/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3B</SO><CO>   TOYOY J.FUT</CO><IN>TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><LP>   TOKYO -- Japan's Toyota Motor Corp. and Fujitsu Ltd.agreed to establish a company to develop and marketengineering software, the two companies said.   The joint venture, Toyota System Research Inc., will beset up next month in Nagoya, with Toyota taking a 65%interest and computer maker Fujitsu putting up the remaining35% in the 300 million yen ($2 million) project, Toyota said.</LP><TEXT>   The venture would aim to match Fujitsu's basic knowledgeas a computer maker with Toyota's applied knowledge as acomputer user to develop software capable of responding totechnological advances in laboratory and factory automation,artificial intelligence and computer-aided engineering, orCAE, Toyota said.   The company will initially focus on developing andmarketing software for the automobile industry, chiefly forrapidly expanding CAE applications, Toyota said.   Sales for the first year are targeted at 500 million yen,with a goal of three billion yen annually after five years.   Operations are tentatively scheduled to begin in November,with a work force of 30 people. Over the next five years, thenumber of employees is seen rising to 250.</TEXT></DOC>